===={{abbreviation}}====
'''I'''

# {{US}} (''roadway'') [[interstate]]

===Etymology 1===
Old French ''i'', from Latin ''ī'', from Etruscan [[I]] (i).

====Noun====
'''I''' or '''i''' (''plural'' Is, is, I’s, i’s)
# The ninth letter of the [[Appendix:Roman script|English alphabet]].

===Etymology 2===
Middle English '''I''', '''[[ich]]''', from Old English '''[[ic]]''', from common Germanic ''*ik'', possibly from a preform '''{{IPAchar|*ekaⁿ}}''' from Proto-Indo-European '''{{IPAchar|keǵóm}}''', '''{{IPAchar|*eǵHóm}}''', or directly from '''{{IPAchar|*éǵoH}}'''. Near cognates include Gothic [[ik#Gothic|ik]], German [[ich]], Frisian [[ik#Frisian|ik]], and Dutch [[ik#Dutch|ik]]; and by extension related to Icelandic [[ég#Icelandic|ég]], Norwegian [[jeg#Norwegian|jeg]], Swedish [[jag#Swedish|jag]], and Danish [[jeg#Danish|jeg]].

====Personal pronoun====
'''I''' (''plural'' [[we]]; ''possessive adjective:'' [[my]])
# The speaker or writer her/himself (the first person singular, '''I''', refers to the speaker or writer alone).

====Inflection====
